Study Roadmap

  1. Python + NumPy Image Basics
     Learn image arrays as H x W x C, RGB channels, pixel ranges [0,255] vs [0,1], resizing, clipping, saving PNGs.

  2. PyTorch Tensor Basics
     Shapes like B x C x H x W, GPU tensors, dtype, .to(device), .detach(), .requires_grad_().

  3. Autograd
     This is essential. Learn how PyTorch records operations, computes gradients with loss.backward(), and stores gradients in parameters.

  4. Optimization With Gradients
     Study gradient descent, Adam, learning rate, gradient clipping, projection/clamping.
     In our code, Adam changes geometry parameters, not Flux weights.

  5. Image Similarity Metrics
     Study MSE, L2, PSNR, SSIM, mean absolute error. These measure whether perturbed.png still looks like original.png.

  6. Latent Space / Embeddings
     A latent is a compressed learned representation. Instead of operating directly on pixels, diffusion models often operate on latent tensors produced by a VAE.

  7. VAE Basics
     Learn encoder, decoder, latent representation, reconstruction.
     In our attack, one objective compares Flux image-conditioning VAE latents between clean and perturbed images.

  8. Text Embeddings / Prompt Embeddings
     Text prompts are converted into vectors/tensors that guide the model.
     In code this is pipe.encode_prompt(...).

  9. Stable Diffusion Architecture
     Study this before Flux: text encoder, VAE, denoising network, scheduler, latents, classifier-free guidance.

  10. Diffusion Denoising Objective
     Learn noise prediction, timestep, scheduler, latent denoising.
     Even though Flux is not exactly classic SD U-Net diffusion, this gives the right mental model.

  11. Flow Matching / Rectified Flow Basics
     Flux-style models are closer to flow-matching transformer systems than old SD U-Nets. Learn how a model predicts a direction/update through latent space.

  12. Flux Architecture
     Focus on these pieces: text encoder, VAE/image conditioning, transformer, latent IDs, timesteps, scheduler, guidance scale.
     You do not need every implementation detail first. You need to know what goes into the transformer and what comes out.

  13. Diffusers Pipeline API
     Learn how Hugging Face Diffusers wraps models. In our scripts, Flux2KleinPipeline gives access to vae, text_encoder, transformer, scheduler, prompt encoding, image
     latents, and final generation.

  14. White-Box vs Black-Box Attacks
     White-box means we use internal model outputs and gradients. Black-box means we only inspect final generated images.

  15. Adversarial Attacks / PGD
     Study pixel PGD first because it is simpler: add small pixel noise, compute a model-disruption loss, update noise by gradient sign, clamp by epsilon.
     See experiment/adversarial_perturbation/scripts/stealth_flux_attack.py:217.

  16. Geometric Perturbations
     Instead of changing pixel colors directly, we move coordinates slightly: each output pixel samples from a nearby input location.

  17. grid_sample
     This is the core geometry tool. It takes an image and a sampling grid, then produces a warped image.
     Study normalized coordinates [-1,1], align_corners=True, bilinear sampling, padding modes.
     See experiment/next_methods/geometric_whitebox/scripts/geo_whitebox_attack.py:713.

  18. Displacement Fields
     Learn dx, dy fields in pixels. A field says “move this pixel by this many pixels horizontally/vertically.”

  19. Rolling Shutter Warp
     Row-dependent horizontal shift: sine wave + shear + acceleration.
     See experiment/next_methods/geometric_whitebox/scripts/geo_whitebox_attack.py:552.

  20. Low-Resolution Grid / Free-Form Deformation
     Learnable small grid, upsampled to full image. Smooth, controllable geometry.
     See experiment/next_methods/geometric_whitebox/scripts/geo_whitebox_attack.py:592.

  21. DCT / Spectral Coordinate Warp
     Smooth displacement built from low-frequency cosine basis functions. Very important for subtle geometry.
     See experiment/next_methods/geometric_whitebox/scripts/geo_whitebox_attack.py:330.

  22. TPS / Thin Plate Spline
     Sparse control points produce a smooth global warp.
     See experiment/next_methods/geometric_whitebox/scripts/geo_whitebox_attack.py:347.

  23. RBF Interpolation
     Another way to spread sparse control-point movements smoothly over the image.

  24. Delaunay / Piecewise Affine Warps
     Fixed triangle mesh, optimized vertex offsets, barycentric interpolation.
     See experiment/next_methods/geometric_whitebox/scripts/geo_whitebox_attack.py:376.

  25. Face Masks / Local Warps
     Warps can be restricted around face, eyes, mouth, jaw, etc. This matters because humans notice face distortion quickly.

  26. Method Gates
     Gates let the optimizer reduce some methods toward zero. This is how the attack can “choose” which perturbation families matter.

  27. Regularization
     Learn why we penalize visible distortion: visual MSE, displacement size, smoothness, foldovers, method L1, gate L1.

  28. Jacobian / Foldover Penalty
     A warp can become invalid if it folds the image over itself. The Jacobian determinant detects that.
     See experiment/next_methods/geometric_whitebox/scripts/geo_whitebox_attack.py:765.

  29. Feature Hooks
     PyTorch forward hooks capture hidden transformer activations during a forward pass. We used these for hidden-feature and attention-proxy losses.

  30. DeepFace / Identity Metrics
     Study SFace, OpenFace, Facenet, Facenet512 only after the attack basics. These are evaluation tools, not the main attack.

  The Exact Loss Idea

  In experiment/next_methods/geometric_whitebox/scripts/geo_whitebox_attack.py:937, Flux is frozen. The optimizer only changes geometry parameters theta.

  The attack creates:

  warped = T_theta(original)

  Then it maximizes Flux disruption while penalizing visible geometry:

  loss =
    - FluxObjective(clean, warped)
    + lambda_visual * image_mse
    + lambda_disp * displacement_size
    + lambda_smooth * total_variation
    + lambda_fold * foldover_penalty
    + lambda_method_l1 * method_displacement_l1
    + lambda_gate_l1 * gate_l1

  Because Adam minimizes loss, the negative sign means it maximizes the Flux objective.

  Flux objectives used:

  vae:
    MSE(clean_image_condition_latents, warped_image_condition_latents)

  transformer_pred:
    MSE(clean_noise_prediction, warped_noise_prediction)

  hidden_feature:
    MSE(clean_transformer_hidden_features, warped_transformer_hidden_features)

  attention_proxy:
    same idea, but hooks attention-like modules

  hybrid:
    transformer_pred + small VAE term

  hybrid_hidden:

  denoise_latent:
    compare clean vs warped latent trajectory after several denoising steps

